 1438","1437":"1437","1436":"1436","1413":"1413","1435":"1435","1501":"1501","1434":"1434","1478":"1478","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1386":"1386","before May 1455":"vóór mei 1455","after 1433":"na 1433","1438":"1438","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Schotland","Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Schotland"},"en":{"before 8 Nov 1438–after February 1492/3":"before 8 November 1438–after February 1493","1433–1501":"1433–1501","1435–Male":"1435–Deceased","1436–Male":"1436–Deceased","1437–1481":"1437–1481","1438–1493":"1438–1493","–Female":"Deceased","–1478":"–1478","1413–1455":"1413–1455","1386–1434":"1386–1434","from 8 June 1478 to February 1493":"from 8 June 1478 to February 1493","1493":"1493","1481":"1481","after February 1492/3":"after February 1493","before 8 Nov 1438":"before 8 November 1438","1437":"1437","1436":"1436","1413":"1413","1435":"1435","1501":"1501","1434":"1434","1478":"1478","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1386":"1386","before May 1455":"before May 1455","after 1433":"after 1433","1438":"1438","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Johnstone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Johnston  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Johnston","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name, deriving in most cases from the place so called in Annandale, in Dumfriesshire. This is derived from the genitive case of the personal name   John   + + Middle English <i>ton</i> ‘town, village, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i>). There are other places in Scotland so called, including the city of Perth, which used to be known as <i>Saint John's Toun</i>, and some of these may also be sources of the surname.","English: habitational name from Johnson Hall (Staffordshire), recorded as <i>Johanneston</i><i>c.</i> 1233 and <i>Joneston</i> in 1314. The placename means ‘John's settlement’, from the genitive case of the Middle English personal name <i>Johan</i>, <i>Jon</i> (see   John  ) + Middle English <i>ton</i> ‘town, village, settlement’.","History: As far as can be ascertained, most Scottish bearers of this surname are descendants of John, probably a Norman baron from England, who held lands at Johnstone in Annandale from the Bruce family in the late 12th century. His son Gilbert was the first to take the surname Johnstone and their descendants later held the earldom of Annandale."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Johnstone of that Ilk was born before 8 November 1438, in Dumfriesshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Adam Johnstone Of that Ilk, was 11435 and his mother, Janet Dunbar, was 52. He had at least 1 son with Unknown. He died after February 1493."},"et":{"before 8 Nov 1438–after February 1492/3":"enne 8. novembrit 1438–pärast veebruari 1493","1433–1501":"1433–1501","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1436–Male":"1436–Surnud","1437–1481":"1437–1481","1438–1493":"1438–1493","–Female":"Surnud","–1478":"–1478","1413–1455":"1413–1455","1386–1434":"1386–1434","from 8 June 1478 to February 1493":"8. juuni 1478 kuni veebruar 1493","1493":"1493","1481":"1481","after February 1492/3":"pärast veebruari 1493","before 8 Nov 1438":"enne 8. novembrit 1438","1437":"1437","1436":"1436","1413":"1413","1435":"1435","1501":"1501","1434":"1434","1478":"1478","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1386":"1386","before May 1455":"enne maid 1455","after 1433":"pärast 1433","1438":"1438","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"before 8 Nov 1438–after February 1492/3":"ennen vuotta 8. marraskuuta 1438–helmikuu 1493 jälkeen","1433–1501":"1433–1501","1435–Male":"1435–Kuollut","1436–Male":"1436–Kuollut","1437–1481":"1437–1481","1438–1493":"1438–1493","–Female":"Kuollut","–1478":"–1478","1413–1455":"1413–1455","1386–1434":"1386–1434","from 8 June 1478 to February 1493":"vuodesta 8. kesäkuuta 1478 vuoteen helmikuu 1493","1493":"1493","1481":"1481","after February 1492/3":"helmikuu 1493 jälkeen","before 8 Nov 1438":"ennen vuotta 8. marraskuuta 1438","1437":"1437","1436":"1436","1413":"1413","1435":"1435","1501":"1501","1434":"1434","1478":"1478","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1386":"1386","before May 1455":"ennen vuotta toukokuu 1455","after 1433":"1433 jälkeen","1438":"1438","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotlan